{
  "texts": [
    "This shared common sense, which emerges from the community's collective discourse, allows individuals to exercise what Hannah Arendt calls an \"enlarged mentality,\" considering the perspectives of others within the community.",
    "116 For Arendt, judgment is not about universal truths or subjective preferences but instead is about making claims of validity that require the agreement of others who are also judging subjects.",
    "117 This agreement is possible because of the shared common sense within the community, which provides a framework for understanding and evaluating competing claims.",
    "118 Thus, judgment-including legal and bureaucratic judgment-is inherently communal.",
    "It depends on a collective exercise of thought and reflection that goes beyond the individual, engaging the community in a process of mutual validation and understanding."
  ]
}